<h1>Problem 1187 - 2019 IMOSL, G4, G</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 7</h2>
<p>Let \(P\) be a point inside triangle \(ABC\). Let \(AP\) meet \(BC\) at \(A_1\), let \(BP\) meet \(CA\) at \(B_1\), and let \(CP\) meet \(AB\) at \(C_1\). Let \(A_2\) be the point such that \(A_1\) is the midpoint of \(PA_2\), let \(B_2\) be the point such that \(B_1\) is the midpoint of \(PB_2\), and let \(C_2\) be the point such that \(C_1\) is the midpoint of \(PC_2\). Prove that points \(A_2, B_2\), and \(C_2\) cannot all lie strictly inside the circumcircle of triangle \(ABC\).</p>
